  {
    "index": 3,
    "hash": "41MrNCyuuxlyPa98SZJOBgh29a4=",
    "timestampUtcMs": "2026-05-13T13:00:31.000Z",
    "action": {
      "type": "SET_CONTENT",
      "input": {
        "content": "Not every copy of the data plays the same role. Evaluating duplication requires understanding what each copy is for:\n\n| Copy | Where | Purpose | Can recover from it alone? |\n|---|---|---|:---:|\n| PGlite | Browser | Fast local reads, UI rendering | No (ephemeral) |\n| PostgreSQL | Switchboard | Multi-device sync, team collaboration, server-side processing | Yes (authoritative) |\n| Swarm /bytes | Decentralized network | Censorship-resistant backup, serverless recovery, wallet-based access | Yes (self-sovereign) |\n\n**Key points**:\n- PGlite is **not** a recovery store \u2014 it's a performance layer. Losing it is annoying but not catastrophic as long as a remote exists.\n- PostgreSQL and Swarm are both recovery-complete, but with different trust models: PostgreSQL requires a server operator, Swarm requires only a wallet signature.\n- Switchboard supports server-side processing (document models, auth, etc.); Swarm alone does not.\n- Swarm is censorship-resistant in ways PostgreSQL cannot be.\n\n**Consequence**: \"duplicate\" is the wrong frame for comparing Switchboard and Swarm. They are **alternative recovery stores** with different trust and capability profiles. Only when both run simultaneously (Architecture C) does the word \"duplicate\" genuinely apply \u2014 and even then the motivation is redundancy, not waste.",
        "updatedAt": "2026-05-13T13:00:31.000Z"
      },
      "timestampUtcMs": "2026-05-13T13:00:31.000Z"
    }
  },
